We consider a regression problem of the form $$ y = \boldsymbol x^T\boldsymbol\beta + \epsilon\,,\quad \epsilon \sim \mathcal N(0, \sigma^2) $$ where $\boldsymbol x\in\mathbb{R}^D$ are inputs and $y\in\mathbb{R}$ are noisy observations. The parameter vector $\boldsymbol\beta\in\mathbb{R}^D$ parametrizes the function and we attempt to find its optimal value for the data and subsequent unseen test data.

We assume we have a training set $(\boldsymbol x_n, y_n)$, $n=1,\ldots, N$ and summarize the sets of training inputs in $\mathcal X = \{\boldsymbol x_1, \ldots, \boldsymbol x_N\}$ and corresponding training targets $\mathcal Y = \{y_1, \ldots, y_N\}$, respectively. Of course, $\boldsymbol x_i$ refers to the $i^{th}$ row of a larger matrix $\boldsymbol X_{n \times d}$, as discussed in lectures.

We are interested in finding parameters $\boldsymbol\beta$ that map the inputs well to the ouputs. However, the optimal $\boldsymbol\beta$ can be found in multiple different ways, each with their own advantages and optimal suggestion.

For general regression problems of the above form we need to add a column of ones as the first column of $\boldsymbol X$. This is to add a neccessary intercept term to our regression. For simplicity, we will add this column of ones inside each function, maintaining $\boldsymbol X$ to be the matrix initialised above.

1.1 ^¶

1.1.2¶

Linear Regression¶

From the lectures, we know that the simplest suggestion for $\boldsymbol\beta$ can be found by optimizing following equation: $$ \underset{\boldsymbol\beta}{\text{min}} \| \mathcal Y - \mathcal X \boldsymbol\beta \|^2 = \underset{\boldsymbol\beta}{\text{min}} \ \text{L}_{\text{LS}} (\boldsymbol\beta) $$ where $\text{L}_{\text{LS}}$ is the (ordinary) least squares loss function. The solution is $$ \boldsymbol\beta^{*} = (\boldsymbol X^T\boldsymbol X)^{-1}\boldsymbol X^T\boldsymbol y \ \in\mathbb{R}^D\,, $$ where $$ \boldsymbol X = [\boldsymbol x_1, \ldots, \boldsymbol x_N]^T\in\mathbb{R}^{N\times D}\,,\quad \boldsymbol y = [y_1, \ldots, y_N]^T \in\mathbb{R}^N\,. $$

The same estimate of $\boldsymbol\beta$ we can be obtained by maximum liklihood estimation which gives statistical interpretation of linear regression. In maximum likelihood estimation, we can find the parameters $\boldsymbol\beta^{\mathrm{ML}}$ that maximize the likelihood $$ p(\mathcal Y | \mathcal X, \boldsymbol\beta) = \prod_{n=1}^N p(y_n | \boldsymbol x_n, \boldsymbol\beta)\,. $$ From derivations discussed in lectures, we know that the maximum likelihood estimator is given by $$ \boldsymbol\beta^{\text{ML}} = (\boldsymbol X^T\boldsymbol X)^{-1}\boldsymbol X^T\boldsymbol y \, . $$

Throughout this notebook we run functions and compute values in a pythonic way, calling functions within functions. The maximum likelihood estimate for the given training set can be found as follows:

In [7]:
def max_lik_estimate(X, y):
    '''
    Find the optimal beta parameters using least squares optimisation.
    '''
    X_aug = np.hstack([np.ones((X.shape[0],1)), X])  # Augment X to add a column of ones.
    N, D = X_aug.shape
    betas_ml = np.linalg.solve(X_aug.T @ X_aug, X_aug.T @ y)
    return betas_ml

def predict_with_estimate(X_test, betas):
    '''
    Predict each entry in the test output vector y using a vector of beta parameters.
    '''
    X_test_aug = np.hstack([np.ones((X_test.shape[0],1)), X_test])  # Augment X to add a column of ones. We will not comment this for the remainder of the notebook.
    prediction = X_test_aug @ betas
    return prediction
In [10]:
def find_R_squared_score(X, y, betas):
    '''
    Find the R^2 score using a vector of beta parameters
    '''
    e = y - predict_with_estimate(X, betas)  # The error for each entry.
    SSres = e.T @ e
    
    y_bar = sum(y)/len(y)
    SStot = np.sum([(y_i - y_bar)**2 for y_i in y])
    
    R_squared_score = 1 - SSres/SStot
    return R_squared_score

The $R^2$ score can be interpreted as the fraction by which the variance of the errors is less than the variance of the dependant variables. Equivalently, the $R^2$ score is equal to the square of the correlation between the dependant variables and the model's predictions for them; the $R^2$ score is determined by the pairwise correlations amongst all of the dependant and independant variables in the model. The adjusted $R^2$ is a modified version of $R^2$ that has been adjusted for the number of predictors in the model. The adjusted $R^2$ score increases when a new predictor improves the model (more than would be expected by chance) and decreases if a predictor does not improve the model.

From the table above, we can see that approximately 87\% of the training data can be explained by and fits our regression model. Furthermore, we see that approximately 86\% of our test data fits the least squares linear regression model trained on the training data set, suggesting our regression model is a good fit. As expected, the out-of-sample $R^2$ score is lower than the in-sample score, but only slightly. This indicates that the model is not over fitting to the training data and can generalise to explain new data sets of the same variety.

The normal $R^2$ score, however, has some drawback. Namely, every time you add a new predictor to the model the $R^2$ score increases meaning a model with many predictors may appear to be a better fit simply because it has more terms. In addition, a model with too many predictors starts to model the random noise in the data and essentially overfits to the training data set. The adjusted $R^2$ score alleviates these pitfalls by taking into account the number of predictors. Our similarly high adjusted $R^2$ scores, for both in-sample and out-of-sample data, display the goodness of fit of our regression model.

Whilst not necessary in least squares linear regression, in ridge and Lasso regression we need to work with standardised data. This is to ensure that all variables contribute equally to the regression, regardless of their respective size. As such, we standardise our training and testing data sets:

def standardise(X):
    '''
    Standardise the columns of a matrix.
    '''
    mu = np.mean(X, 0)
    sigma = np.std(X, 0)
    X_std = (X - mu) / sigma
    return X_std
In [16]:
def get_mus_and_stdvs(X):
    '''
    Get the mean and standard deviation of each column.
    '''
    mu = np.mean(X, 0)
    sigma = np.std(X, 0)
    mus_and_stdvs = []
    for i in range(X.shape[1]):
        mus_and_stdvs.append([mu[i], sigma[i]])
    return mus_and_stdvs

A natural extension of linear regression is ridge regression, which induces sparsity into the model, reducing the number of descriptors, but simultaneously introducing bias into the estimator. We will see that whilst the ridge estimator is a biased estimator it (potentially) results in a lower variance than the least squares unbiased estimator, consequently reducing the model's mean-squared error and generally providing a better regression model for unseen test data sets.

Ridge regression introduces a small, positive penalty term $\lambda$ that penalises large values of $\| \boldsymbol\beta \|$ leading to smaller $\beta_i$ coefficients. We attempt to minimise the ridge loss function:

$$ \underset{\boldsymbol\beta}{\text{min}} \ \text{L}_{\text{ridge}} (\boldsymbol\beta) = \underset{\boldsymbol\beta}{\text{min}} \| \mathcal Y - \mathcal X \boldsymbol\beta \|^2 + \lambda \| \boldsymbol\beta \|^2 $$

From lectures, we know that this can be solved explicitly by taking the derivative and using matrix algerbra. The solution is

$$ \boldsymbol\beta^{*}_{\text{ridge}} = (\boldsymbol X^T\boldsymbol X + \lambda I)^{-1}\boldsymbol X^T\boldsymbol y \, . $$

In [21]:
def ridge_estimate(X, y, penalty):
    '''
    Find the optimal beta parameters using ridge regression.
    '''
    N, D = X.shape
    X_aug = np.hstack([np.ones((N,1)), X])
    N_aug, D_aug = X_aug.shape
    I = np.identity(D_aug)
    I[0, 0] = 0  # Intercept term removed to improve the shrinkage properties of ridge regression so that it is not dominated by large values of the intercept of the linear model.
    
    beta_ridge = np.linalg.inv(X_aug.T @ X_aug + penalty * I) @ X_aug.T @ y
    
    return beta_ridge
In [22]:
def folds_func(y, k):
    '''
    Find the indices for a vector split into k folds.
    '''
    return np.split(np.arange(len(y) - len(y)%k), k)  # We make the size of each fold equal to maintain simplicity. In the training data this will only miss out a single data point.
In [23]:
def k_fold_average_MSE_ridge_estimate(X, y, k, penalty):
    '''
    Find the average ridge mean-squared error for a particular penalty and k-fold cross-validation.
    '''
    folds = folds_func(y, k)
    MSEs = []
    
    for i in range(len(folds)):
        test_indices = folds[i]
        train_indices = list(set(range(len(y))) - set(test_indices))
        
        X_train = X[train_indices][:]
        y_train = y[train_indices]
        X_test = X[test_indices][:]
        y_test = y[test_indices]
        
        betas = ridge_estimate(X_train, y_train, penalty)
        e = y_test - predict_with_estimate(X_test, betas)
        SSres = e.T @ e
        MSEs.append(SSres/len(e))  # Append this fold's MSE to the list.

    average_MSE = sum(MSEs)/k  # Calculate the average across folds.
    return average_MSE

It can be easily shown that

$$ \text{MSE(}\hat{\theta}) = E[(\hat{\theta} - \theta)^2] = \text{Var(}\hat{\theta}) + \text{bias(}\hat{\theta})^2. $$

Of course, this can be extended to the multivariate case such that

$$ \text{MSE(}\hat{\underline{\theta}}) = E[(\hat{\underline{\theta}} - \underline{\theta})^2] = \text{Trace(Cov(}\underline{\hat{\theta}})) + \text{bias(}\underline{\hat{\theta}})^T\text{bias(}\underline{\hat{\theta}}). $$

In essence, this tells us that Model Error = Reducible Error + Irreducible Error.

According to this derivation of the mean-squared error, we can graphically depict why introducing bias into our parameter estimation, but simultaneously reducing the model's variance, can lead to a lower mean-squared error than the un-biased least squares estimation:

We note that graph plots Bias$^2$ as-opposed to Bias, hence the optimal value for the mean-squared error is at their crossing point.

Despite the fact that we do not know the true value of our $\beta_i$ estimators, we can make a naive approximation of them using our least squares estimation since it is un-biased. As such, we can naively mimic the above plot using our training data. We note that the following plot is merely to portray the general trend of bias, variance and mean-squared error as a function of the penalty parameter, since we do not have the true values for either $\boldsymbol{\beta}$ or $\sigma^2$.

Since ridge regression is equivalent to linear regression for $\lambda = 0$, and linear regression is un-biased, we have that $\lambda = 0 \implies \text{MSE(}\hat{\theta}) = \text{Var(}\hat{\theta}).$ As such, we can scale the sample variance calculated below such that, at $\lambda = 0$, the sample variance is equal to the cross-fold mean-squared error calculated above. Whilst this in no-way constitues $\textit{correct}$ mathematical manipulation, it does allow us to nicely observe the general trend of bias, variance and mean-squared error as a function of the penalty parameter.

def naive_ridge_bias(X, y, penalty):
    '''
    Find the naive approximation for the bias, using the least squares estimation for the true beta.
    '''
    betas = ridge_estimate(X, y, penalty)
    bias = betas_ml - betas
    return bias
In [27]:
def ridge_covariance(X, y, penalty):
    '''
    Find the sample covariance matrix.
    '''
    N, D = X.shape
    X_aug = np.hstack([np.ones((N,1)), X])
    N_aug, D_aug = X_aug.shape
    I = np.identity(D_aug)
    I[0][0] = 0
    
    mean_of_ys = np.mean(predict_with_estimate(X, ridge_estimate(X, y, penalty)))
    difference =  predict_with_estimate(X, ridge_estimate(X, y, penalty)) - mean_of_ys
    
    sample_error_variance = (difference.T @ difference) / (N_aug - D_aug)
    covariance = sample_error_variance * (np.linalg.inv(X_aug.T @ X_aug + penalty * I) @ X_aug.T @ X_aug) @ (np.linalg.inv(X_aug.T @ X_aug + penalty * I)).T
    return covariance

We can therefore see some very distinct trends as the penalty hyper-parameter is increased. Firstly, as previously discussed, the mean-squared error intially decreases, converging to its minimum point, before increasing at a rate dominated by the bias$^2$. This re-emphasis how the introduction of bias to an estimator can lead to a better model fit due to the corresponding reduction in variance. Additionally, we can see that the bias increases and the variance decreases as the penalty hyper-parameter is increased.

1.3 ^¶

1.3.1¶

We now implement a relaxation of Lasso regression, where we attempt to optimise the cost function given by:

$$ L_{Lasso}(\beta) = \| \textbf{y} - X \boldsymbol{\beta} \|^2 + \lambda \sum_{i}^{p} L_c(\beta_i) $$

where $L_c(\beta)$ is the differential Huber function such that

$$ L_c(\beta_i) = \begin{cases} \frac{1}{2} \beta^2 & \text{for } |\beta| \leq c, \\ c(|\beta| - \frac{1}{2}c) & \text{otherwise.} \end{cases} $$

Lasso regression is similar to ridge regression in that it implements a penalty term that penalises large $\beta_i$s. However, by construction, the Lasso penalty term leads to more a more direct selection of parameters: small $\beta_i$s in ridge regression will be sent to 0, reducing the number of parameters involved in the model. Despite there not existing an analytical solution for Lasso regression, we can optimise our solution using iterative convex optimisation techniques. In this notebook we will implement gradient descent.

In [33]:
def huber(beta, c=1e-6):
    '''
    Find the huber function applied to each entry of a given vector.
    '''
    betas = np.zeros(shape=(len(beta),))
    for i in range(beta.shape[0]):
        if abs(beta[i]) <= c:
            betas[i] = 1/2 * beta[i]**2
        else:
            betas[i] = c * (abs(beta[i]) - 1/2 * c)     
    return betas
  
def grad_huber(beta, c=1e-6):
    '''
    Find the gradient of the huber function applied to each entry of a given vector.
    '''
    betas = np.zeros(shape=(len(beta),))
    for i in range(beta.shape[0]):
        if abs(beta[i]) <= c:
            betas[i] = beta[i]
        else:
            betas[i] = np.sign(beta[i]) * c
    return betas

In [35]:
def minimize_ls_huber(X, y, penalty, n_iters=10000, step_size=1e-2):
    '''
    Find the betas that minimise the Lasso regression cost function via iterative gradient descent.
    '''
    n, p = X.shape
    X_aug = np.hstack([np.ones((n,1)), X])
    p+= 1  # To account for the change in X's dimensions.
    betas = np.zeros(p)  # Initialise the betas.

    # Implement gradient descent for n_iters iterations. The gradient is found by differentiating the Lasso cost function.
    for i in range(n_iters):
        grad = -2/n * X_aug.T @ (y - X_aug @ betas) + penalty * np.concatenate([np.zeros([1]), grad_huber(betas[1:])])
        betas = betas - step_size * grad  # Gradient descent update.
        
    return betas

def k_fold_average_MSE_lasso_estimate(X, y, k, penalty):
    '''
    Find the average Lasso mean-squared error for a particular penalty and k-fold cross-validation.
    '''
    folds = folds_func(y, k)    
    MSEs = []
    
    for i in range(len(folds)):
        test_indices = folds[i]
        train_indices = list(set(range(len(y))) - set(test_indices))
        
        X_train = X[train_indices][:]
        y_train = y[train_indices]
        X_test = X[test_indices][:]
        y_test = y[test_indices]  
        
        betas = minimize_ls_huber(X_train, y_train, penalty)
        e = y_test - predict_with_estimate(X_test, betas)
        SSres = e.T @ e
        MSEs.append(SSres/len(e))

    average_MSE = sum(MSEs)/k
    return average_MSE

2.1 ^¶

2.1.1¶

The k-Nearest Neighbours algorithm can be used both for classification and regression. Having standardised our data so that each column (equivalently, each feature) has a mean of zero and a variance of one, we can calculate the distance of a given test data point $x$ to all other points in the training data set. We then find the k points closest to $x$ and assign the new point $x$ to the majority class of the k nearest points. In this notebook we will work with the Euclidean distance

$$ d(\boldsymbol p, \boldsymbol q) = \sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^D{(q_i-p_i)^2}} \, , $$

where $\boldsymbol p$ and $\boldsymbol q$ are the two points in our $D$-dimensional Euclidean space.

In [49]:
def euclidian_distance(p, q):
    '''
    Find the Euclidean distance between two points p and q.
    '''
    return np.sqrt(np.sum((p-q)**2, axis=1))
In [50]:
def k_neighbours(X_train, X_test, k):
    '''
    Find the indices of the k-nearest neighbours in the training data to each point in the testing data.
    '''
    dist = []
    neigh_ind = []
  
    point_dist = [euclidian_distance(x_test, X_train) for x_test in X_test]  # Compute the distance from each point in X_test to all points in X_train.
    
    for row in point_dist:
        enum_neigh = enumerate(row)
        sorted_neigh = sorted(enum_neigh, key=lambda x: x[1])[:k]

        ind_list = [tup[0] for tup in sorted_neigh]  # Determine the indices of the k training points closest to each test point.
        dist_list = [tup[1] for tup in sorted_neigh]

        dist.append(dist_list)
        neigh_ind.append(ind_list)

    return np.array(neigh_ind)
In [51]:
def predict(X_train, y_train, X_test, k):
    '''
    Predict the classification for each data point in the test data, given the training data and its classification.
    '''
    neighbours = k_neighbours(X_train, X_test, k)
    y_pred = np.array([np.argmax(np.bincount(y_train[neighbour])) for neighbour in neighbours])  # Choose the label with the most number of occurences.
    return np.array(y_pred)
In [52]:
def kNN_predict(X, y, k, number_of_folds=5):
    '''
    Implement 5-fold cross-validation on the training data to find the optimal value of the hyper-parameter k.
    '''
    N, D = X.shape
    n_neighbours = k
    folds = folds_func(y, number_of_folds)
    y_prediction = np.zeros(shape= (N - N%number_of_folds))
    
    if number_of_folds == 1:
        y_pred = predict(X, y, X, k)
        y_prediction += y_pred
        
    else:
        for i in range(len(folds)):
            test_indices = folds[i]
            train_indices = list(set(range(len(y))) - set(test_indices))

            X_train = X[train_indices][:]
            y_train = y[train_indices]
            X_test = X[test_indices][:]
            y_test = y[test_indices]

            y_pred = predict(X_train, y_train, X_test, k)
            y_prediction[test_indices] += y_pred
    
    return y_prediction
In [53]:
def number_correct_predictions(X, y, k, number_of_folds=5):
    '''
    Count the number of correct predictions for a particular k and 5-fold cross-validation.
    '''
    correct = 0
    kNN_prediction = kNN_predict(X, y, k, number_of_folds)
    for i in range(len(y) - len(y)%number_of_folds):
        if y[i] == kNN_prediction[i]:
            correct += 1

    return correct
In [54]:
def kNN_score(X, y, k, number_of_folds=5):
    '''
    Find the fraction of predictions that are correct for a particular k and 5-fold cross-validation.
    '''
    return number_correct_predictions(X, y, k, number_of_folds)/(len(y) - len(y)%number_of_folds)

def accuracy(true, prediction):
    '''
    Find the accuracy of a set of predictions for a given set of true values.
    '''
    correct = 0
    
    for i in range(len(true)):
        if prediction[i] == true[i]:
            correct += 1
            
    accuracy = correct/len(true)
    return accuracy

2.2 ^¶

We now train a random forest classifier on the data set, employing cross-entropy as the information criterion for the splits in the decision tree.

To determine $j$ and $s$ at each split node, we search for $j$ and $s$ that minimizes the weighted sum of Cross-Entropy of the left side samples and right side samples:

$$CE(\boldsymbol y; j, s) = p_l \times CE(\boldsymbol y_l) + p_r \times CE(\boldsymbol y_r)$$

where $p_l$ and $p_r$ are, respectively, the cumulative weights of samples on the left and on the right, while $CE(\boldsymbol y)$ is defined as:

$$ \text{CE}(\boldsymbol y) = - \sum_{i=1}^Q \mathbb P (y = c_i) \cdot \log(\mathbb P (y = c_i)) $$

where $c_i$ is the i-th class out of $Q$ distinct classes, so $\mathbb P (y = c_i)$ reads the weight of the class $i$ in the current sample $\boldsymbol y$.

In doing this minimisation, with an unseen data point we can traverse successive splits in the random forest and attain a prediction for the classification of this unseen data point, based on the path it took down each decision tree. We will optimise our random forest based on the hyper-parameters: number of decision trees and depth of trees. One might naively think that the optimal values for each of these hyper-parameters would be as high as possible but this is not the case for a more general model: we do not want to overfit our model to the training data rendering it ineffective for unseen data sets of the same variety.

In [66]:
training_weights = np.ones_like(diagnosis) / len(diagnosis)  # Initialise the initial weights to all be equal and sum to one.

We want to allow the code to consider samples with different weights to maintain generality, hence introduce an additional argument called sample_weights in the cross-entropy index function.

In [67]:
def ce_index(y, sample_weights):
    """ 
    Calculate the cross-entropy-index for labels.
    """
    label_weights = {yi: 0 for yi in set(y)}  # Initialize with zero for each distinct label.
    for yi, wi in zip(y, sample_weights):
        label_weights[yi] += wi  # Count different labels in  and store in label_weights
    total_weight = sum(label_weights.values())
    ce = 0
    
    for label, weight in label_weights.items():
        ce -= (weight / total_weight) * np.log(weight/total_weight)

    return ce

Next, we define a function to split the data samples based on a feature (column) index and a value. This will be called in later functions. We note that since all of the data is numeric, we do not need to implement an additional method for splitting categorical data.

In [69]:
def split_samples(X, y, sample_weights, column, value):
    """
    Return the split of data whose column-th feature is less than value.
    """ 
    left_mask = (X[:, column] < value)

    X_left, X_right = X[left_mask, :], X[~left_mask, :]
    y_left, y_right = y[left_mask], y[~left_mask]
    w_left, w_right  = sample_weights[left_mask], sample_weights[~left_mask]

    return (X_left, X_right), (y_left, y_right), (w_left, w_right)

For a given feature index, we need to estimate the best value $s$ to use as threshold. We need to implement the function that searches for $s$ and minimizes the ce-index. We do this by calling our previously defined functions split_samples and ce_index.

In [70]:
def ce_split_value(X, y, sample_weights, column):
    """
    Calculate the ce-index based on `column` with the split that minimizes the ce-index.
    """
    unique_vals = np.unique(X[:, column])
    ce_index_val, threshold = np.inf, None

    # Split the values of the i-th feature and calculate the cost.
    for value in unique_vals:
        (X_l, X_r), (y_l, y_r), (w_l, w_r) = split_samples(X, y, sample_weights, column, value)

        p_left = sum(w_l)/(sum(w_l) + sum(w_r))
        p_right = 1 - p_left
        new_cost = p_left * ce_index(y_l, w_l) + p_right * ce_index(y_r, w_r)
        if new_cost < ce_index_val:
            ce_index_val, threshold = new_cost, value

    return ce_index_val, threshold

We now choose the best feature to split by calling the function ce_split_value for each feature.

In [72]:
def ce_split(X, y, sample_weights, printing=False):
    """
    Choose the best feature to split according to criterion - we want the smallest ce-index value.
    """
    min_ce_index, split_column, split_val = np.inf, None, 0  # split_column = None means there is no valid split at the current node.
    
    for column in range(X.shape[1]):
        if len(np.unique(X[:, column])) < 2:  # Skip column if samples are not seperable by that column.
            continue
        ce_index, val = ce_split_value(X, y, sample_weights, column)
        if ce_index < min_ce_index:
            min_ce_index, split_column, split_val = ce_index, column, val
            if printing:
                print('Current minimum Cross-Entropy index =', ce_index)

    return split_column, split_val

We need a function that returns the label which appears the most in our label variable y.

In [74]:
def majority_vote(y, sample_weights):
    """
    Return the label which appears the most in y.
    """
    majority_label = {yi: 0 for yi in set(y)}
    
    for yi, wi in zip(y, sample_weights):
        majority_label[yi] += wi
        
    return max(majority_label, key=majority_label.get)

We can now build the decision tree by using ce_split to find the best feature to split the data X and split_samples to get sub-trees.

In [76]:
def build_tree(X, y, sample_weights, feature_names, depth, max_depth=3, min_samples_leaf=2):
    """
    Build the decision tree according to the data.
    Returns:
      (dict): a dict denoting the decision tree (binary-tree). Each node has seven attributes:
        1. 'feature_name': The column name of the split.
        2. 'feature_index': The column index of the split.
        3. 'value': The value used for the split.
        4. 'majority_label': For leaf nodes, this stores the dominant label. Otherwise, it is None.
        5. 'left': The left sub-tree with the same structure.
        6. 'right' The right sub-tree with the same structure.
    """
    # Include a clause for the cases where (i) no feature, (ii) all labels are the same, (iii) depth exceed, or (iv) X is too small.
    if len(np.unique(y))==1 or depth>=max_depth or len(X)<=min_samples_leaf: 
        return {'majority_label': majority_vote(y, sample_weights)}

    split_index, split_val = ce_split(X, y, sample_weights, printing=False)

    if split_index is None:
        return {'majority_label': majority_vote(y, sample_weights)}  # If no valid split at this node, use majority vote.

    (X_l, X_r), (y_l, y_r), (w_l, w_r) = split_samples(X, y, sample_weights, split_index, split_val)
    
    return {
      'feature_name': feature_names[split_index],
      'feature_index': split_index,
      'value': split_val,
      'majority_label': None,
      'left': build_tree(X_l, y_l, w_l, feature_names, depth + 1, max_depth, min_samples_leaf),
      'right': build_tree(X_r, y_r, w_r, feature_names, depth + 1, max_depth, min_samples_leaf)
    }

We define a wrapper function train to call this build_tree function with the appropriate arguments.

def train(X, y, sample_weights=None):
    """
    Build the decision tree according to the training data.
    """
    if sample_weights is None:
        sample_weights = np.ones(X.shape[0]) / X.shape[0]  # If the sample weights are not provided we assume the samples have uniform weights.
    else:
        sample_weights = np.array(sample_weights) / np.sum(sample_weights)

    feature_names = list(pd.DataFrame(pd.read_csv('tumour_samples.csv')).columns[1:])
    return build_tree(X, y, sample_weights, feature_names, depth=1)

We now want to use this fitted decision tree to make predictions for our unseen test data set. We first define a function classify that takes each single data point x as an argument. We write a wrapper function predict that calls this classify function.

In [80]:
def classify(tree, x):
    """
    Classify a single sample with the fitted decision tree.
    """
    if tree['majority_label'] is not None: 
        return tree['majority_label']

    else:
        if x[tree['feature_index']] < tree['value']:
            return classify(tree['left'], x)
        else:
            return classify(tree['right'], x)
In [81]:
def predict(tree, X):
    """
    Predict classification results for X.
    """
    if X.shape[0] == 1:
        return classify(tree, X)
    else:
        return np.array([classify(tree, x) for x in X])

To evaluate how well the tree can generalise to unseen test data set, we define a function that computes the mean accuracy.

def tree_score(tree, X_test, y_test):
    '''
    Find the mean accuracy of the prediction.
    '''
    y_pred = predict(tree, X_test)
    return np.mean(y_pred==y_test)

Whilst this clearly suggests our tree is capable of classifying the data (in that it has a higher success probability than random selection), the current hyper-parameters are most likely not currently optimised. As such, we will now embed the above formulation of an individual classification tree into an ensemble model called a random forest.

We will apply bootstrapping and aggregating methods for multiple decision trees upon two levels. Firstly, we will bootstrap on the training instances: each model is trained on a random-sample (with replacement) from the training-instances. Secondly, we will explore multiple depths for each individual tree, using an ensemble of models to predict our optimal variable. As such, this design leaves us with two hyper-parameters to optimise: B, the number of decision trees and max_depth, the maximum depth of each tree.

In [84]:
def ce_split_rf(n_features, X, y, sample_weights):
    """
    Choose the best feature to split according to criterion - we want the smallest ce-index value.
    """
    columns = np.random.RandomState(seed=99).choice([i for i in range(X.shape[1])], n_features, replace=False)
    min_ce_index, split_column, split_val = np.inf, 0, 0
    
    for column in columns:
        if len(np.unique(X[:, column])) < 2:  # Skip column if samples are not seperable by that column.
            continue
        ce_index, val = ce_split_value(X, y, sample_weights, column)  # Search for the best splitting value for the given column.   
        if ce_index < min_ce_index:
            min_ce_index, split_column, split_val = ce_index, column, val

    return min_ce_index, split_column, split_val

We can then modify build_tree to call ce_split_rf instead of ce_split as before.

In [85]:
def build_tree_rf(n_features, X, y, sample_weights, feature_names, depth,  max_depth=10, min_samples_leaf=2):
    """
    Build the decision tree according to the data.
    Returns:
      (dict): a dict denoting the decision tree (binary-tree). Each node has seven attributes:
        1. 'feature_name': The column name of the split.
        2. 'feature_index': The column index of the split.
        3. 'value': The value used for the split.
        4. 'majority_label': For leaf nodes, this stores the dominant label. Otherwise, it is None.
        5. 'left': The left sub-tree with the same structure.
        6. 'right' The right sub-tree with the same structure.
    """
    # Include a clause for the cases where (i) all lables are the same, (ii) depth exceed (iii) X is too small.
    if len(np.unique(y)) == 1 or depth>=max_depth or len(X)<=min_samples_leaf: 
        return {'majority_label': majority_vote(y, sample_weights)}

    else:
        ce, split_index, split_val = ce_split_rf(n_features, X, y, sample_weights)

        # If the cross-entropy is infinity, it means that samples are not seperable by the sampled features.
        if ce == np.inf:
            return {'majority_label': majority_vote(y, sample_weights)}
        
        (X_l, X_r), (y_l, y_r), (w_l, w_r) = split_samples(X, y, sample_weights, split_index, split_val)
        
        return {
            'feature_name': feature_names[split_index],
            'feature_index': split_index,
            'value': split_val,
            'majority_label': None,
            'left': build_tree_rf(n_features, X_l, y_l, w_l, feature_names, depth + 1, max_depth, min_samples_leaf),
            'right': build_tree_rf(n_features, X_r, y_r, w_r, feature_names, depth + 1, max_depth, min_samples_leaf)
        }

We can now write the training function that calls build_tree_rf and constructs multiple decision trees, each operating on a subset of samples (with replacement).

In [86]:
def train_rf(B, n_features, X, y, sample_weights=None, max_depth=2):
    """
    Build the decision tree according to the training data.
    """
    if sample_weights is None:
        sample_weights = np.ones(X.shape[0]) / X.shape[0]  # If the sample weights are not provided we assume the samples have uniform weights.
    else:
        sample_weights = np.array(sample_weights) / np.sum(sample_weights)  # Normalise the vector of weights.

    N = X.shape[0]
    training_indices = np.arange(N)
    trees = []
    feature_names = list(pd.DataFrame(pd.read_csv('tumour_samples.csv')).columns[1:])

    for _ in range(B):
        sample = np.random.choice(training_indices, N, replace=True)
        X_sample = X[sample, :]
        y_sample = y[sample]
        w_sample = sample_weights[sample]
        tree = build_tree_rf(n_features, X_sample, y_sample, w_sample, feature_names, depth=1, max_depth=max_depth)
        trees.append(tree)

    return trees

We can now write a prediction function which aggregates the decision from all decision trees and returns the class with highest probability.

In [87]:
def aggregate(decisions):
    '''
    Aggregate the decisions and find the class with the highest probability.
    '''
    count = defaultdict(int)
    for decision in decisions:
        count[decision] += 1
    return max(count, key=count.get)
In [88]:
def predict_rf(rf, X):
    """
    Predict classification results for X.
    """
    if len(X.shape) == 1:
        return aggregate([classify(tree, X) for tree in rf])
    else:
        return np.array([aggregate([classify(tree, x) for tree in rf]) for x in X])
In [89]:
def rf_score(rf, X_test, y_test):
    '''
    Find the mean accuracy of the prediction.
    '''
    y_pred = predict_rf(rf, X_test)
    return np.mean(y_pred==y_test)

In [92]:
def B_tree_average_MSE_rf(X, y, B, d, k=5):
    '''
    Find the average random forest mean-squared error for a particular number of decision trees and depth.
    '''
    
    folds = folds_func(y, k)
    MSEs = []
    
    for i in range(len(folds)):
        test_indices = folds[i]
        train_indices = list(set(range(len(y))) - set(test_indices))
        
        X_train = X[train_indices][:]
        y_train = y[train_indices]
        X_test = X[test_indices][:]
        y_test = y[test_indices]
        
        rf = train_rf(B, n_features, X_train, y_train, sample_weights=None, max_depth=d)
        score = rf_score(rf, X_test, y_test)
        MSEs.append(score)

    average_MSE = sum(MSEs)/k
    return average_MSE

def best_Bd_pair(X, y, k, B_range, d_range):
    '''
    Find the optimal values for the hyper-parameters B and d, according to the average mean-squared error a model with these parameters returns. 
    '''
    B_scores = np.zeros((len(d_range), len(B_range)))
    
    for j, B in enumerate(B_range):
        for i, d in enumerate(d_range):
            B_scores[i, j] = B_tree_average_MSE_rf(X, y, B, d, k=5)
            print(f'Cross-Validated Accuracy at depth={d}, #trees={B}: {B_scores[i, j]:8f}')
            
    best_B_index = np.argwhere(B_scores==B_scores.max())
    print(B_scores)
    print(best_B_index)
    return (d_range[best_B_index[0][0]], B_range[best_B_index[0][1]])

We therefore see that our optimal hyper-parameters are:

Number of decision trees = 3
Maximum tree depth = 3

It is interesting to note that the maximum depth is a far more influential hyper-parameter in determining the accuracy of a random forrest compared with the number of trees. This makes sense because low maximum depth values often lead to the model underfitting the data, potentially wrongly classifying borderline data points. Additionally, the optimal number of decision trees being 3 as opposed to 2 or 1 implies that B = 3 lead to the model arbitrarily choosing decision trees that were more effective at modelling the entire data set. In subsequent iterations, it would be perfectly feasible for B = 1 or B = 2 to be the optimal number of trees (although less likely than 3, simply due to the reduction in variance).

2.2.2¶

We can now define a function to compute the confusion matrix for a given random forest and input test data set. The confusion matrix allows is a summary of prediction results on a classification problem and defined as follows:

In [126]:
def conf_matrix(rf, X_test, y_test):
    '''
    Find the confusion matrix for a given random forest classification and test data set.
    '''
    y_pred = predict_rf(rf, X_test)
    mat = np.zeros((2, 2))
    
    for true, pred in zip(y_test, y_pred):
        if true == 1 and pred == 1:
            mat[0, 0] += 1
        elif true == 0 and pred == 0:
            mat[1, 1] += 1
        else:
            mat[true, pred] += 1
    
    return mat

We can define some additional functions, based on the confusion matrix, that help us analyse the classification's success.

In [136]:
def recall(mat):
    return mat[0, 0] / (mat[0, 0] + mat[1, 0])

def specificity(mat):
    return mat[1, 1] / (mat[1, 1] + mat[0, 1])

def accuracy(mat):
    return (mat[0, 0] + mat[1, 1])/ np.sum(mat)

def precision(mat):
    return mat[0, 0] / (mat[0, 0] + mat[0, 1])

def fscore(mat):
    return 2 * precision(mat) * recall(mat) / (precision(mat) + recall(mat))

We therefore see that our optimised random forest is a good classifier for both itself and the unseen test data. For the sample confusion matrix, an accuracy of 0.97 suggests that almost all of the sample data can be classified using just three seperations, showing the data to be very seperable. In fact, this could have been anticipated since the kNN optimal hyper-parameter was k = 1, suggesting the data is distinctly clustered into its repective classes. Whilst the accuracy for the unseen test data is lower, given that it is over 80% accurate itself we can ascertain that the random forrest is also an effective classifier of unseen data. In essence, this suggests that the random forest does not overfit or underfit the data. The recall, which measures the true positive rate, is actually higher for the unseen test data than the recall for the sample data. We assume that this is due to the uneven distribution of the data: the sample data has approximately 20% 'Malignant' data points whereas the test data has approximately 38% 'Malignant'. Due to the increased propensity of 'Malignant' data points in the test data, it is more likely they are distinctly in the 'Malignant' region; anomolies are less significant. In addition, this could simply be due to how the data has been collected - it is a possibility that the test data contains very easy to determine 'Malignenet' data points and they are therefore well classified. Despite this 20:80 split of the sample data into 'Benign' and 'Malignant' data points, the sample confusion matrix's specificity (the true negative rate) of 0.99 implies that the model is more successful at predicting 'Benign' tumours (classification 0) and generally has a bias towards making a 'Benign' classification for a data point. This enforces the argument that the 'Malignant' data points in the test data set are easily determined since the test data confusion matrix's specificity is only 0.76.

We also see that the F-score for the test data set is 0.92 whereas for the test data set it is 0.79. The F-score is the harmonic mean of the precision and recall, and can be interpreted as a measure of accuracy that is robust even when the data is unevenly distributed. For example, if we have data with a large class inbalance, such as our training data where only 20% of the data is 'Malignant', a model that classifies all the data as 'Benign' (much like our classifier does on the test data set) would return an accuracy of 0.8, despite being useless on real-world data sets. As such, the F-score tackles this by returning an accuracy measure that is robust even when the data is unevenly distributed. An F-score for the test data of 0.79, which is close to the accuracy score of 0.82, suggests that the classifier continues to work well despite the uneveness of the test data (compared to the sample data) and is therefore a good model. However, given our assumption that the sample data set and the test data set are from of the same variety and therefore share the same characteristics, we would hope to acheive a higher accuracy and F-score for the test data set. It would be fair to assume to that the influential parameters in the test data set are less influential in the training data set and therefore not reached by the depth of the tree, which has been set to a maximum of 3. Given more time and computing power it would be interesting to observe this change in accuracy and F-score on the test data set as the maximum depth of the tree is increased and properly hollistically determine the optimal maximum depth for each data set.

For support vector machine classification it makes our calculations simpler to classify our prediction variables as -1 and 1 (instead of 0 and 1 as before) and we implemeent this change below:

Support vector machine classification can be intuitively thought of in term of distances: we wish to find the hyper plane through the data that will lead to the greatest distance between the two closest points on either respective side. This is often referred to as finding the 'widest street'. Of couse, perfect data sets, where the data points are seperable in d-dimensional space, rarely exist. We can therefore relax this hard classification to the softer case of imperfect classification, where the introduction of a penalty term penalises violations to the seperation of our hyper-plane. In this softer case, we allow support vector machine classification to make a certain number of mistakes and keep the margin as wide as possible so that other points can still be classified correctly.

Our aim is the minimise the hinge loss function $$ \mathcal L (\boldsymbol w) = \frac{1}{2} \| \boldsymbol w \|^2 + \frac{\lambda}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \max \bigg( 0, 1-y_i (\boldsymbol w \cdot x_i + b) \bigg) \, . $$ where $\boldsymbol w$ is the vector of weights, $\lambda$ the regularisation parameter, and $b$ the intercept which is included in our X as an additional column of $1$'s.

In [142]:
def compute_cost(w, X, y, regul_strength=1e5):
    '''
    Find the value of the cost function for a set of data and its wieghts.
    '''
    n = X.shape[0]
    distances = 1 - y * (X @ w)
    distances[distances < 0] = 0  # Equivalent to max(0, distance).
    hinge = regul_strength * distances.mean()
    return 0.5 * np.dot(w, w) + hinge

An effective way to optimize the cost is by using a stochastic gradient descent algorithm. In order to use stochastic gradient descent, we need to implement a function for the cost gradients with respect to $w$.

In [143]:
def calculate_cost_gradient(w, X_batch, y_batch, regul_strength=1e5):
    '''
    Find the gradient of the cost function with respect to w.
    '''
    # If only one example is passed
    if type(y_batch) == np.float64:
        y_batch = np.asarray([y_batch])
        X_batch = np.asarray([X_batch])  # Gives multidimensional array.

    distance = 1 - (y_batch * (X_batch @ w))
    dw = np.zeros(len(w))
    
    for ind, d in enumerate(distance):
        if max(0, d)==0:
            di = w
        else:
            di = w - (regul_strength * y_batch[ind] * X_batch[ind])
        dw += di

    return dw/len(y_batch)  # Return the average.

We can now call both of the two previous functions in sgd to update the weights iteratively with a given learning rate $\alpha$. We also implement a stop criterion that ends the learning as soon as the cost function has not changed more than a manually determined percentage. This is to maintain efficiency in our code.

We know that the learning happens through updating the weights according to $$ \boldsymbol w = \boldsymbol w - \alpha \frac{\partial \mathcal L}{\partial \boldsymbol w} $$

where $\frac{\partial \mathcal L}{\partial \boldsymbol w}$ is the gradient of the hinge loss we have computed in the previous cell.

In [144]:
def sgd(X, y, batch_size=16, max_iterations=2000, stop_criterion=0.01, learning_rate=1e-5, regul_strength=1e5, print_outcome=False, graph=False):
    '''
    Implement stochastic gradient descent with a given learning rate.
    '''
    weights = np.zeros(X.shape[1])  # Initialise zero weights
    nth = 0
    prev_cost = np.inf  # Initialise starting cost as infinity
    indices = np.arange(len(y))
    if graph:
        graph_vals = []
    
    for iteration in range(1, max_iterations):
        np.random.RandomState(seed=64).shuffle(indices)  # Shuffle to prevent repeating update cycles.
        batch_idx = indices[:batch_size]
        X_b, y_b = X[batch_idx], y[batch_idx]
        for xi, yi in zip(X_b, y_b):
            ascent = calculate_cost_gradient(weights, xi, yi, regul_strength)
            weights = weights - (learning_rate * ascent)

        # Visualise the convergence on every 2^n'th iteration.
        if iteration==2**nth or iteration==max_iterations-1:
            cost = compute_cost(weights, X, y, regul_strength)
            if print_outcome:
                print("Iteration is: {}, Cost is: {}".format(iteration, cost))
            if graph:
                graph_vals.append(cost)
            # Stop criterion.
            if abs(prev_cost - cost) < stop_criterion * prev_cost:
                if graph:
                    return graph_vals
                return weights
              
            prev_cost = cost
            nth += 1
    
    return weights

We can now train the model with our sample data set. We use an arbitrary penalty term since we only wish to observe the general trend of our results at this stage.

def score(w, X, y):
    '''
    Find the mean accuracy of our predcitions for a given set of weights.
    '''
    y_preds = np.sign(X @ w)

def cross_val_evaluate(X, y, num_folds=5, regul_strength=1e3, printing=False):
    '''
    Implement 5-fold cross-validation to find the accuracy for a particular penalty term, regul_strength.
    '''
    folds = folds_func(y, num_folds)
    train_scores = []
    val_scores = []
    
    for i in range(len(folds)):
        val_indices = folds[i]
        train_indices = list(set(range(X.shape[0])) - set(val_indices))

        X_train = X[train_indices][:]
        y_train = y[train_indices]
        X_val = X[val_indices][:]
        y_val = y[val_indices]

        # Train the model.
        w = sgd(X_train, y_train, max_iterations=1025, stop_criterion=0.01, learning_rate=1e-5, regul_strength=regul_strength)
        train_score = score(w, X_train, y_train)
        val_score = score(w, X_val, y_val)
        
        if printing:
            print('Fold', i+1)
            print("Training finished.")
            print("Accuracy on train set #{}: {}".format(i+1, train_score))
            print("Accuracy on validation set #{}: {}".format(i+1, val_score))

        train_scores.append(train_score)
        val_scores.append(val_score)

    return np.mean(train_scores), np.mean(val_scores)

def find_best_penalty_SVM(X, y, num_folds, penalty_range, show=False, printing=False):
    '''
    Find the optimal value for the penalty hyper-parameter.
    '''
    penalty_scores = np.zeros((len(penalty_range),))
    
    for i, penalty in enumerate(penalty_range):
        penalty_scores[i] = cross_val_evaluate(X, y, num_folds, penalty)[1]
        if printing:
            print(f'Cross-Validation Accuracy at penalty = {penalty}: {penalty_scores[i]:.5f}')
    out = (penalty_range[np.argmax(penalty_scores)], max(penalty_scores))
    if show:
        plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
        plt.scatter(penalty_range, penalty_scores)
        plt.scatter(out[0], out[1], color='red', marker='x')
        plt.title('Accuracy Score vs Penalty Hyper-parameter')
        plt.xlabel('penalty')
        plt.ylabel('accuracy scores from cross validation')
        plt.show()
        
    return out

We can clearly see that as the penalty parameter is increased, and therefore the hardness of the model is decreased, the accuracy of the model increases. This suggests that the best performing hyper-planes used to split the data have data points on either side of their 'widest street' that they allow, but class as mistakes. The seemingly grouped together and horizontal data points in the above plots are where multiple $\lambda s$ lead to the same number of tolerated mistakes when finding the optimal hyper-plane through the data; each value of $\lambda$ leads to the same optimal hyper-plane being selected. However, there is a limit to how lenient it can be to mistakes before this leniency is no longer explicitly advantageous. Having said this, the high accuracy for our hard support vector machine suggests that our data is already well seperated and therefore any degree of softening the constraints can only improve the model. It is important to note that with support vector machine classifiers, slight changes to either the data set or the penalty hyper-parameter can have drastic effects on the model's accuracy. This accounts for the more sporadic graph directly above.

We can explore this further via receiver operating characteristic curves.

The Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve aims to capture the model output probabilities (or scores) into the quantification of the model performance. The ROC curve can be constructed by computing True Positive Rate (TPR) and False Positive Rate (FPR) for a range of thresholds. An ideal model would have Area Under the Curve (AUC) of 1, while a model with random decisions would have an AUC of 0.5. This AUC can be computed using the trapezoidal rule.

In [120]:
def logistic(x):
    '''
    Convert each data point to a probability using the logistic function.
    '''
    return 1 / (1 + np.exp(-x))
In [124]:
def roc_curve(y_true, y_log):
    """
    Returns:
    auc: area under the curve (AUC).
    tpr_l: a list of true positive rate (TPR) values for each scanned threshold.
    fpr_l: a list of false positive rate (FPR) values for each scanned threshold.
    thresholds: the scanned thresholds sorted descendingly.
    """
    thresholds = reversed(sorted(set(y_log)))  # List the distinct values in y_log and sort descendingly.
    tpr_l, fpr_l = [], [] 

    for threshold in thresholds:
        y_thresholded = (y_log >= threshold)  # Apply thresholding.

        tp = np.sum(y_true & y_thresholded)  # True positives.
        tn = np.sum((~y_true) & (~y_thresholded))  # True negatives.
        fp = np.sum((~y_true) & y_thresholded)  # False positives.
        fn = np.sum(y_true & (~y_thresholded))  # False negatives.

        tpr = tp / (tp + fn)
        fpr = fp / (tn + fp)
        tpr_l.append(tpr)
        fpr_l.append(fpr)

    auc = np.trapz(tpr_l, fpr_l)  # Compute the area under curve (AUC) using the Trapezoidal rule.
    return auc, tpr_l, fpr_l, thresholds
In [175]:
def roc_plots(penalties, X, y, X_test, y_test):
    '''
    Plot the Receiver Operating Characteristic curve for multiple penalty values.
    '''
    aucs = []
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 15))
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'r--')
    
    for penalty in penalties:
        w = sgd(X, y, regul_strength=penalty)
        y_pred = X_test @ w
        
        y_log = logistic(y_pred)
        boolean_y_test = np.array([int(y) if y > 0 else 0 for y in y_test])  # Return to boolean form.
        auc, tpr, fpr, th = roc_curve(boolean_y_test, y_log)
        aucs.append(auc)
        
        plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve', size=20)
        ax = plt.subplot(111)
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f'penalty = {penalty}, AUC = {auc}')
        box = ax.get_position()
        ax.set_position([box.x0, box.y0 + box.height * 0.1, box.width, box.height*0.9])
        
        plt.ylabel('TPR', size=20)
        plt.xlabel('FPR', size=20)
        
    max_ind = np.argmax(aucs)  # Get the best auc and penalty.
    penalty_max = penalties[max_ind]
    m = np.max(aucs)
    print(f'The optimal penalty is {penalty_max} with an area under the curve of {round(m, 5)}.')
    
    ax.legend(loc='upper center', bbox_to_anchor=(0.5, -0.5), fancybox=True, shadow=True, ncol=6)
    ax.legend().set_visible(False)
    handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
    plt.show()
    
    axe = plt.subplot()
    axe.legend(handles, labels, ncol=6, loc='upper center')  # Show the legend.
    plt.axis('off')
    ax.legend().set_visible(False)
    plt.show()
    
    return (penalty_max, m)

It is clear from the above plot that the balanced data set is better modelled using a hard classifier. This is expected since the data is no longer unevenly distributed, outliers and anomolies become less significant. However, as the balanced model's softness is increased, the accuracy decreases. This examplifies an important aspect to consider when training a model on a data set: it is important the data set is an accurate representation of the generla population. It is well known that 'Malignant' tumours are far less common than 'Benign' tumours, and therefore a balanced data set is an imperfect representation of the population. As such, the classifier incorrectly predicts more data points in the test data set, since it has a scewed view of how frequent each class of tumour is in the population the balanced data set has been taken from. The AUC is the probability that a classifier will rank a randomly chosen positive instance ('Malignant') higher than a randomly chosen negative instance ('Benign'). It measures the classifiers skill in ranking a set of patterns according to the degree to which they belong to the positive class. The accuracy, however, whilst still depending on the ability of the classifier to rank patterns, also depends on its ability to select a threshold in the ranking used to assign patterns to the positive class if above this threshold and to the negative class if below it. As such, a penalty with high AUC but with a lower accuracy will rank patterns well but select the threshold badly. This is exemplified above, as the optimal $\lambda$ according to accuracy ($\lambda = 1$ along with the other $\lambda$s returning this accuracy) is actually the worst performer according to AUC. This shows that using a balanced data set, that is not representative of the test data you are going to classify on, will scew the results offering different optimal hyper-parameters according to different optimisation criterion. We note that this can in fact be advantageous, and will depend on the data used to train the classifier and its aim. For example, a 'Malignant' tumour is far more dangerous than a 'Benign' tumour, and we would therefore prefer to class all 'Malignant' tumours correctly with some additional false positives than have high accuracy but an increase in false negatives.
